helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma:
Ping shows the connection quality (the ping) from you to the connection you have selected on the map. It is measured in milliseconds ('ms'). If Auto-Ping is enabled in your Geo-Filter Map then the ping shown is the ping from you to the host / server of your game.

Host Tick Rate measures the amount of packets sent per second from the host of your game, usually a server, to you. The higher, the better.

Client Tick Rate measures the amount of packets per second you are sending to the host of your game.

Send Rate measures the amount of data sent per second from the host of your game, usually a server, to you.

Receive Rate measures the amount of data per second you are sending to the host of your game.

helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma:
VPN Traffic is used to select the devices and services you want to apply your VPN to. Before applying any rules, make sure you have successfully setup your VPN. See the VPN Setup panel to do this.

Once you have successfully logged into your VPN provider on your router, click Add Device and select the device you want to apply your VPN to. After adding a device, the entire device will be in the VPN. But if you just want to apply the VPN to a specific service, you can select from one of the following modes:

  • Do not VPN these services will apply the VPN to every service on your device except the services you choose. For example, you could apply the VPN to your PC but exclude a game like League of Legends from the VPN.
  • Only VPN these services will only apply the VPN to the services you select. For example, you could apply the VPN to Skype on your PC, but all other applications on your PC will not be sent through the VPN.

With the VPN mode selected, select the services you wish to either exclude or include in your VPN. Click the Add Service button to bring up a pre-set list of popular services. Click Advanced if you wish to manually add a port rule instead.
goodputEnabledInformation@/dumaos/apps/u: Each packet has a header usually about 40 - 60 bytes out of 1500 bytes. Bandwidth allocation includes the header by default so for a test like speedtest which doesn't measure headers it will seem like your speed is lower than it is. Goodput means assign extra bandwidth to accommodate the headers so your bandwidth is closer to the speedtest result.
helpContentTwo@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netd:
Ping Assist enhances your Geo-Filter by allowing servers or players are located outside your Geo-filter range to connect to you if they have a low ping.

For example, if only servers in the UK were allowed by your settings, but a server in Germany tried to connect to you, Ping Assist will allow the connection if it has a ping value less than your Ping Assist number.

We recommend you set your Ping Assist value between 30ms and 50ms to begin with. Any connection below that number will be allowed to connect to you. You can then increase or decrease this value based on your personal preference.

To disable Ping Assist, set the value to 0ms.
Your sliders are still set to 100%. This means your games could still be caught in a queue, causing lag. Lower your sliders below 100% to limit the total bandwidth the greedy devices can take. This makes room for your smaller applications, eliminating the queuing problem.

helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma:
A virtual private network ('VPN') is used to mask your real IP addresses from the Internet. When a VPN connection is made, the VPN server replaces your real IP address with an IP address from the VPN server, keeping your home Internet connection secure.

Hybrid VPN offers far more control than a regular router VPN. Instead of applying your VPN to your entire network, you can choose the individual devices you would like the VPN to be applied to. For example, your console, your PC, and/or your phone. You can also choose specific services you then want in the VPN. For example, you could choose to just apply your VPN to Skype on your PC, or a specific port range.

This means you can protect the devices or services that need it, without forcing the rest of your network to go through a VPN which is usually slower than a normal connection.

To setup a VPN on your router, click on VPN Setup. You need an active subscription to a VPN provider so you will be asked to enter your VPN provider details. If you do not have a provider, there are many options available if you look online.

You can either choose a VPN provider from the preset list found in Basic setup, or you can use the Advanced setup and input your VPN provider's OpenVPN config file (most VPN providers can give you this).

Once you have successfully logged into your VPN provider on your router you then need to choose how you would like the VPN to be applied. See the VPN Traffic panel for next steps.

Block Traffic If VPN Disconnects will disable your Internet connection if your VPN is disconnected. If you check this box, then you will not be able to access the Internet if your VPN goes down. We only recommend checking this box if you are extra sensitive about your security.

helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma: Allow & Deny lets you whitelist or blacklist specific connections. These settings will supersede your other Geo-Filter settings. Choosing to Allow another connection will mean they can always connect to you, even if they are outside your allowed areas. Choosing to Deny another connection will mean it will always be blocked, even when it is inside an allowed area. To either Allow or Deny, left click on the connection on your Geo-Filter Map. Then in the Ping panel that opens on the right hand side, choose either ALLOW or DENY.

specatingSuccessMessage@/dumaos/apps/usr: You have added your PC game to the Geo-Filter. As most PC games do not require filtering, you are in 'Spectating Mode'. This will show the server you have connected to and your ping, but it will not be blocked.
You cannot ping when using the Geo-Filter on the Dashboard. Click on the Geo-Filter on the left-hand menu to access the full Geo-Filter feature set.
helpContent2@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: By default, DumaOS prioritizes DumaOS Classified Games, which is a preset list of games and covers all console games and most PC games. You can manually add your own service or port/port range by clicking ADD DEVICE and then choosing the service or port/port range you would like to add.

step14Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdu: Network congestion creates a queue, which forces games and other fast applications to wait. Traffic Prioritization guarantees that these fast applications will always be placed at the front of the queue, reducing lag.

step1Content@/www/desktop/tour.html: DumaOS is a state-of-the-art router operating system designed to optimise your home's connection and crush lag.
always100AlertContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/c: Your sliders are still set to 100%. This means your games could still be caught in a queue, causing lag. Lower your sliders below 100% to limit the total bandwidth the greedy devices can take. This makes room for your smaller applications, eliminating the queuing problem.
autoDST@/www/desktop/time-selector.html: Automatically adjust for daylight savings time
step5Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: Set the radius to a size you want by dragging the Distance slider. We recommend 1000km - 2000km (621 miles - 1,242 miles). The radius prevents all connections outside its range from hosting your game.
step9Content@/www/desktop/tour.html: See which devices are connected to your router and block any unwanted devices.
step4Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: You can move a pinned panel on the Dashboard by clicking and holding the Rapp's name in the header at the top of the panel and then moving your mouse. Release the click button to set the new position. Your changes will be automatically saved.
step7Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: That completes the setup for the Device Manager Rapp. If you need further help, click on each panel's Help Icon for more information.
routerRebootingConfirmation@/www/desktop: Your router is now rebooting. This should take 3-4 minutes.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: View the current utilization of your router's CPUs. The number(s) will be higher when there are more processes running on your router.
step7Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: When Auto Ping Host is enabled (toggle in the Geo-Filter Map Options), a ping graph will automatically load when you are in a game. Otherwise, you can manually click on any icon on the map to load a ping graph for that connection. If you wish to view the ping graph on your Dashboard you will need to enable Auto Ping Host.
step1Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: System Information shows information about your router, such as CPU usage and a list of your installed Rapps.
step1Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: When devices in your home are using all the bandwidth, it creates congestion and queuing. This causes games and other low-latency applications to lag. QoS gives you the complete toolset to solve this problem. The first tool to setup is Congestion Control, which prevents greedy devices from maxing out your bandwidth.
upgradeConfirmationMessage@/www/desktop/: Are you sure you want to upgrade?
step12Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdu: Click Update Distribution to save your changes to Bandwidth Allocation.
step6Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: Some devices need more bandwidth than others, such as a PC on Netflix. With Bandwidth Allocation, you can control how your bandwidth is shared across all your devices.
autoHyperlaneDisableWarning@/dumaos/apps: Disabling Auto Traffic Prioritization means your router will no longer automatically apply Traffic Prioritization when it detects high priority traffic, such as games. Instead, you will need to add services and their devices to Traffic Prioritization manually. Re-enable Auto Traffic Prioritization if you would prefer the router to do this naturally.
httpsUnsupportedMessage@/www/desktop/chr: You have chosen to access DumaOS using HTTPS on Chrome which is not supported. Please switch to HTTP using the buttons below, or if you require HTTPS because you are accessing your router remotely, please use an alternative browser such as Firefox.
qosApplicationFailedError@/dumaos/apps/u: QoS failed to apply. If the problem persists please reboot your router.
drawerHelpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.n:
Kilometres / Miles toggles the units shown for distance.

Strict Mode guarantees that dedicated servers outside of your filter range will always be blocked. This should be ticked when searching in most games, except Destiny where we recommend this box is unticked.

Auto Ping Host will automatically load a ping graph which shows the quality of your connection to your game's host / server. When unchecked, you will need to manually click the host's icon on the Geo-Filter map (usually this the icon which never disappears).

Zoom Factor adjusts the zoom level on the Geo-Filter Map. The higher the number, the greater the zoom. After setting the Zoom Factor, click on the Magnifying Glass icon on the Geo-Filter Map and then click on the location you wish to zoom closer in on.

Flush Cloud reloads the Geo-Filters IP list. It is only necessary to select this option if you have been advised to by technical support.

Fast Search is an add-on to Ping Assist. Enabling Fast Search makes Ping Assist work much faster, which should make finding games quicker. However, this may occasionally mean you allow a connection that is above your Ping Assist limit. If you would prefer to avoid this, disable Fast Search. This may result in longer search times.

emptyMessage@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: This page is blank because you have not pinned any panels to your personalised Dashboard. Click the Pin icon in the top right-hand corner of your favourite panels to view them on this screen.
step8Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: If you wish to whitelist or blacklist a connection, click its icon on your Geo-Filter Map and then choose Allow or Deny in the Ping panel.
